Men are afraid of women.&nbsp; In Ancient Greece virgin women were considered wild and were only tamed through marriage.&nbsp; This is also reflected in the Greek goddesses, particularly Artemis and Athena.&nbsp; Both are virgin goddess, immune to the persuasion of Aphrodite and rather masculine in their pursuits.&nbsp; Artemis the protector of young animals, yet the patron of hunters and the protector of wild spaces, usually wooded areas.&nbsp; Athena, the patron of her Polis, patron of young heroes and often dressed with helmet, shield, and spear.&nbsp; The Greeks needed these goddesses to remain virgins so that they could remain "wild".&nbsp; 
In the Amazon basin tribes practiced a feast celebration that centered around clitordectomy of marriageable girls.&nbsp; This surgery was based upon their religious belief that women once had penises and ruled the world and were wild.&nbsp; Men, with their culture and domesticity and agriculture now rule and the clitoris was viewed as a vestigial penis.&nbsp; These people also believed that women, with their vestigial penises and their ability to give birth made them "over-sexed" and so, in order to tame the young brides-to-be the clitoris had to be removed.&nbsp; Here again is this sense that women are "wild" and must be tamed, cultured by men.&nbsp; 
In many other societies women are viewed as evil or driving men to evil.&nbsp; Christianity is a great example.&nbsp; Eve convinces Adam to eat the forbidden fruit and brings about the fall of the first man and all humans.&nbsp; Since then it is women who are controlled sexually and must be obedient and kept, and when they go against this it is they that are accused of driving men to lust as if the man were bewitched.&nbsp; This idea that women must be kept "pure" and that they simultaneously contain magic powers of seduction over men is found in many societies ranging from ancient to modern and usually the society tries to invoke restrictions using religion.&nbsp; A more modern example or at least extreme example would be Islamic or Christian militants who impose strict dress codes for women and strict separation of men and women's roles.&nbsp; 

Fear of women seems very old and is often used to repress them.&nbsp; The sad part is, many women also buy into it.&nbsp;

I've taken a three day weekend this weekend.&nbsp; Dr. Murray went out of town for a conference, no wait, out of the country.&nbsp; So, no meeting today.&nbsp; I have taken the weekend and day off.&nbsp; It feels great.&nbsp; Regalo and I hit the trail or at least some land with no fencing.&nbsp; Nicholas walked with us.&nbsp; The weather has just been so beautiful this weekend, especially after last week's constant drizzle (which we did need).&nbsp; 

I finally used my birthday present from my parents.&nbsp; My eyebrows are no longer quite so scary.&nbsp; Serenity Spa is decent, but I'm not sure I don't still like La Rousse better.&nbsp; The last time I went to one of these places was before my wedding.&nbsp; 

I'm taking one class this semester and it's one of Dr. Ajootian's classes.&nbsp; She is wonderful.&nbsp; I'm doing my class project on a Greek neck amphora from c. 550-500B.C.&nbsp; It is mentioned by a few people, but not much has been written about it, so there may be a publishing opportunity.&nbsp; You can see it through the Perseus Project.&nbsp; Their link is on the Links page of Classic's home page.&nbsp; It is in the Robinson Collection.&nbsp; I'm really excited that I'm going to get to actually handle it.&nbsp; This project is helping fill a void I have with my library thesis.&nbsp; Even though I did the surveys with Dr. Murray I'm not going to be doing any more research with any of the artifacts we found.&nbsp; One day I would like to go through all of the steps in analyzing material culture, from finding it, washing it, classifying, etc.&nbsp;

Two Stick's last night of Trivia was fun.&nbsp; Well, they claim they'll have it again once they move in September, but we'll see.&nbsp; The total pool was $1280.&nbsp; My team, which consisted of only three people that I knew before arriving there and ultimately consisted of 10 people sat on the stage.&nbsp; It was hot, but not crowded.&nbsp; We ended up in a 4-way tie and one of the teams was the teabag team.&nbsp; I had it in for them, but that's another matter.&nbsp; We ended up losing to "Bong hits for Jesus" or the ultimate frisbee club.&nbsp; Damn.&nbsp; But, they were gigantic so no one left with much money individually.&nbsp; I'm just glad it wasn't the teabags.&nbsp; 

Apparently the Classicists call ceramic vessels "vases".&nbsp; Aside from strange nomenclature, Dr. Ajootian is a fabulous professor.&nbsp; 

The new alcohol policy on campus embraces fully the county law.&nbsp; Unfortunately UPD once again proves their incompetence and harasses students with coolers that are legal drinking age.&nbsp; I can't wait for the first home game =D

Everyone seems to be moving.&nbsp; I'll probably be about the last to leave and the more leaving becomes a reality the more I like my little town nestled in the hills of North Mississippi.&nbsp; I still have at least a year and a half.&nbsp; 

I am horrible at proper social behavior sometimes.&nbsp; For instance, I am currently tracking down my wedding photographer because I never received my wedding album from him.&nbsp; He's violated a contract and run off with a lot of money.&nbsp; His business is "closed" but hopefully he did not leave town.&nbsp; If I have to I'll go to his doorstep.&nbsp; Two years!&nbsp; Yes, this is partly my fault.&nbsp; If we can't find him then I guess I'm free to take the preview pictures and do what I want.&nbsp; I think his violation sends a clear forfeit of license over the photos.&nbsp; 

I finally drank the koolaid in Germany and read through all six Harry Potter books in the six weeks I was there.&nbsp; Yes, I waited in line at Squarebooks Jr. to pick up my prepaid copy and was even in the first group to go in.&nbsp; I have not, however, finished it yet.&nbsp; I am close and let me just say, wow.&nbsp; Nicholas needs to hurry his ass up on reading the sixth book so he can read this one.&nbsp; 

Just remember folks, Voldemort cannot stop Harry and the Potters!&nbsp;

Hayley, good luck!&nbsp; Charles, awesome view!&nbsp; 

I'm back at work in the Art Department until school starts back and then I'll be at work in the Anthropology Dept.&nbsp; I'll be working for Dr. Murray, which he was very adament about, especially when I mentioned that I might be doing some lab work for Dr. Johnson.&nbsp; I really don't see how grading papers will take 10 hours a week.&nbsp; We'll see.&nbsp; AND, I get to write my thesis this year and I don't think I need to take any classes.&nbsp; I hope not.&nbsp; I'm really looking forward to not having class.&nbsp; 

I helped Nicholas' parents move the day after I got back from Germany.&nbsp; We were going to meet them in Memphis and drive along in the mini.&nbsp; But then, the movers did not show up Friday nor Saturday morning.&nbsp; So, Nicholas and I drove to N. Little Rock, AR.&nbsp; Helped load up a 24' Uhaul and then we hopped into a vehicle (Nicholas and Matt drove the trucks -Penske and Uhaul-Debbie the van and I got the Mini).&nbsp; Due to a late start and an unfortunate mechanical problem with the Uhaul (gas ran out but gas gauge is messed up and the dash lights don't work) we spent the night in Memphis, TN.&nbsp; Then we got to park on I-40 for a while outside of Nashville.&nbsp; We spent the next night in Sevierville outside of Gatlinburg.&nbsp; Then we drove down really steep, twisting mountainsides that, yes, did scare me despite my ultimate driving machine.&nbsp; Finally, we reached Frederick Maryland and their rental house for a year.&nbsp; There three brothers joined us and helped us unload one and half of the trucks.&nbsp; The rest was unloaded the next morning.&nbsp; Once the move from hell ended, we were able to enjoy pleasures of the area such as the many winneries and other agritourist attractions.&nbsp; 

School starts a bit late this year.&nbsp; August 20th, I believe.&nbsp; It will be interesting to see everyone return for school.&nbsp; Those of you who left after graduation, if you come and visit you will somewhat surprised by some of the changes.&nbsp; Oh, and Gispen is taking over Croft and Metcalf is being put in a higher position for something related to international studies.&nbsp; Just for those of you playing the home game....

